"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450683","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>Since National Citizenship Service (NCS) began, over 200,000 young people have taken part in this life changing opportunity. NCS is the fastest growing youth movement in this country for a century, with a 46% increase in the number of participants between 2013 and 2014.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Participants Commence NCS</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Participants Graduated</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>8,400</p></td><td><p>6,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>26,000</p></td><td><p>22,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>39,600</p></td><td><p>32,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>57,800</p></td><td><p>50,900</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The participant figures for 2015 will be published with the 2015 evaluation in due course.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-09T14:10:50.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450683/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450683/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many teenagers have (a) commenced and (b) graduated a National Citizenship Service programme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450684","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Autumn 2015 Spending Review announced over £1 billion to expand the National Citizen Service and the ambition is for NCS to cover 60% of all 16 year olds by 2020/21. The following table shows the funding provided by Government for the delivery of NCS since the programme commenced.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Government Funding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>£21 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£62 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£84 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£130 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-09T14:12:15.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450684/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450684/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been spent on the National Citizenship Service programme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450685","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>Value for money assessments take place yearly as part of the independent evaluation of the National Citizen Service (NCS).</p><p>The most recent 2014 evaluation shows that every £1 spent on NCS generates up to £3.98 of social benefits. This figure quantifies a range of benefits, including the time participants spend volunteering on their social action projects.</p><p>It is estimated by the NCS Trust that NCS participants have volunteered 8 million hours since the programme began in 2011.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-09T14:13:08.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450685/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450685/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent assessment of the value for money of the National Citizenship Service his Department has commissioned or reviewed.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450686","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>National Citizen Service (NCS) Trust receives an annual grant from Cabinet Office. In line with National Audit Office recommendations, the NCS Trust delivers an Annual Reconciliation Statement setting out how funds have been spent. The Cabinet Office publishes details of NCS funding in its Annual Report and the programme is independently evaluated to assess impact and value for money.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-09T14:14:09.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450686/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450686/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","National Citizenship Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, by what method his Department assesses the financial returns of the  National Citizenship Service; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450687","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-12","<p>All charities in receipt of government grants should submit a final budget reconciliation to the grant giver at the end of the grant demonstrating how all funds have been spent on the activities specified in the grant letter. The Cabinet Office’s published standard terms and conditions of the grant includes the right to recover the grant if it has not been used for the purposes and activities agreed or if terms and conditions have not been met.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-12T10:59:33.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450687/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450687/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Charities: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure that charities report surplus funds awarded to them by the Government.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450688","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is delighted to support and endorse the Clean for the Queen initiative. Litter and fly-tipping blight communities and pose a risk to human health, which is why tackling them is a priority for the Government. I gave my backing to the campaign when it was launched and we will continue to promote it, to help reach as many people as possible.</p><p> </p><p>Together with the Minister for Local Government, Marcus Jones MP, I shall be writing to every Member of Parliament with an English constituency and every English unitary and district Local Authority, to encourage their participation and leadership in this worthwhile campaign.</p><p> </p><p>Our experience from the first Community Clear-Up Day in March last year demonstrated the enthusiasm and willingness of people across England to give some of their time to improve their local environment. The Clean for the Queen campaign provides a great opportunity for people to come together and clean up our local streets and parks.</p><p> </p><p>We hope the campaign will help lead to a lasting legacy of a cleaner, tidier Britain.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-10T17:34:04.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450688/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450688/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-04","Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to support the Clean for the Queen campaign.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450689","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>National Citizen Service attracts young people from all backgrounds and walks of life. The latest evaluation showed that 27% of NCS participants were from non-white backgrounds compared with 19% of the comparable general population. Data is not currently held on the proportion of young people from independent schools participating in NCS. However, the Trust will begin to collect this detail this coming summer. Independent schools such as Dulwich College, Leicester Grammar, James Allen's Girls School and Hymers College, along with others, are referring pupils to NCS. NCS is also now featured on the new Independent State Schools Partnership website (<a href="http://www.schoolstogether.org/" target="_blank">www.schoolstogether.org</a>).</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-02-11T12:01:41.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450689/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450689/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the National Citizen Service participants are from (a) independent schools and (b) BME backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450690","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The banks are required to separate by 1 January 2019 and implementation remains firmly on track.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-12T14:21:41.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450690/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450690/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the timetable is for his Department's plans to separate retail and investment banking arms.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450691","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-04","<p>Contributions to the EU are paid directly from HM Government and thus are not attributable to any one part of the UK.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-05-04T15:39:58.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450691/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450691/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","EU Budget: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the value of financial contributions to the EU in 2015 that were attributable to London and the South East of England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450692","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Honorable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-12T14:01:03.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450692/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450692/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information he holds on the reasons why the Financial Conduct Authority has not sought a restitution order against (a) Capita, (b) Blue Gate and (c) the directors of Tinta plc in relation to the Connaught Income Fund.","false","Biography information for Dame Angela Watkinson","Hornchurch and Upminster","Dame Angela Watkinson","25897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450693","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>Autumn Statement 2015 confirmed that the business rates review will report at Budget 2016. The review will be fiscally neutral.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-09T17:04:15.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450693/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450693/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the planned business rate reforms announced in the 2015 Summer Budget have been amended.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450694","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>This government will be spending twice as much in cash terms on apprenticeships by 2020 compared to 2010. Spending on apprenticeships in England will be £2.5bn in 2019-20. The BIS spending review settlement for apprenticeships reflects the government’s commitment regarding the proceeds of the Libor fine the FCA announced in April 2015<em>.</em> Further announcements that support the government’s commitment to delivering employment opportunities for young people will be announced in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-12T14:32:38.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450694/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450694/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Financial Services: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress officials in his Department have made on incorporating the proceeds of the £227 million fine imposed on Deutsche Bank in relation to their Libor activities into a new three-year fund to create 50,000 apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","25976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450695","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government intends that a purchaser who is replacing a main residence (even if owning more than one property) will not be subject to the higher rates of SDLT on purchases of additional properties. A consultation has recently concluded on the higher rates and the final policy design will be confirmed at Budget 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-09T17:08:24.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450695/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450695/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to put measures in place to provide that the proposed higher rate stamp duty land tax will not apply when a purchaser who owns more than one property is replacing a main residence.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450696","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Honorable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-12T14:05:16.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450696/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450696/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Financial Services and Markets Act 2000","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information he holds on the reasons why the Financial Conduct Authority has not made use of the powers granted to it under sections 382 and 384 of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 to require restitution from  parties who by breaking regulatory requirements cause less to others.","false","Biography information for Dame Angela Watkinson","Hornchurch and Upminster","Dame Angela Watkinson","25896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450697","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is required to collect trade in goods statistics by EU legislation. This legislation sets out the detail and frequency of the data to be collected and provided to the EU Commission.</p><p> </p><p>Council Regulation (EC) No 471/2009 and Commission Regulations (EU) No 92/2010 and No 113/2010 set out the requirement for HMRC to collect trade in goods statistics between the UK and non-EU countries. Council Regulation (EC) No 638/2004 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1982/2004 sets out the requirement to collect the corresponding statistics between the UK and other EU Member States.</p><p>HMRC provides trade in goods data to the Office for National Statistics (ONS). As required by the sixth edition of the International Monetary Fund’s Balance of Payments Manual (BPM6) and the European System of Natural and Regional Accounts (ESA 2010), National Accounts and Balance of Payments also include trade in services. The ONS collects this data.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T17:54:06.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450697/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450697/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reason trade statistics are collected on a different basis by HM Revenue and Customs and the Office for National Statistics; and what plans the Government has to align the collection of such data.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","25924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450698","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>UK Trade-in-Goods statistics are mainly compiled using customs documentation for non-EU movements, and via the Intrastat survey for EU movements. Goods which are transhipped through a first country (e.g. for transport reasons) en route to a second are recorded as movements to the ultimate receiving country (subject to the way in which they are declared to HMRC). Goods which are exported to a first country (e.g. for further process) will be recorded as an export to that country.</p><p> </p><p>Quality checks are regularly undertaken by HMRC with regard to all types of movements. More information on the Data Quality checks that are carried out by HMRC can be found in this published document “<a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/OverseasTradeStatistics/AboutOverseastradeStatistics/Documents/OTSMethodology_paper.pdf" target="_blank">Methodology paper for the Overseas Trade Statistics</a>” (<a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/OverseasTradeStatistics/AboutOverseastradeStatistics/Documents/OTSMethodology_paper.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/OverseasTradeStatistics/AboutOverseastradeStatistics/Documents/OTSMethodology_paper.pdf</a>) .</p><p> </p><p>The UK Trade in Goods publication is a National Statistics product, meaning amongst other things, it is recognised for its quality.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-12T13:57:43.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450698/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450698/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of trade statistics collected by the Government on identifying trade flows through second countries (a) in general and (b) where the UK exports a good or service to a first country which is then export on as a finished product.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","25923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450699","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-15","<p>This information is not held centrally. Individual departments are responsible for managing their own debt.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-15T13:37:07.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450699/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450699/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-04","Government: Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Government has spent on debt collection activity in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","25948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450700","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government is determined to crack down on fraud and the compensation culture.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that offers to settle made to claimants without medical evidence may encourage opportunistic and fraudulent claims. The Government introduced new court rules in October 2014 to discourage such offers and we continue to keep the matter of third party capture, including the impacts on motor premiums, under review.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","26008","2016-02-11T10:16:34.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450700/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450700/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to end the offering of compensation in personal injury claims when there is no medical evidence.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","25986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450701","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>A full list of all the projects funded by European Regional Development Fund and European Social Fund in the South East since 2007 are provided on the GOV.UK site.</p><p> </p><p>The total value of grants awarded to organisations in the South East from the Seventh Framework Programme (FP7) 2007-2013 was €1,175.3 million (figure correct at 11/11/2015). The total value of grants awarded to organisations in the South East under the Horizon 2020 (2014-2020) programme is €246.5 million (figure correct at 29/10/2015). The figures for both programmes include grants that were awarded under the complementary Euratom research and training activities programme.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-09T17:13:58.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450701/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450701/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-04","EU Grants and Loans: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which projects in the South East have received European Commission funding in each of the last five years; and how much each such project received in such funding in each such year.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","26007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450702","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government is determined to crack down on fraud and the compensation culture.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that offers to settle made to claimants without medical evidence may encourage opportunistic and fraudulent claims. The Government introduced new court rules in October 2014 to discourage such offers and we continue to keep the matter of third party capture, including the impacts on motor premiums, under review.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","25986","2016-02-11T10:16:34.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450702/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the effect of third party capture on motor insurance premiums.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","26008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450703","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-10","<p>Insurers must pay IPT on the value of premiums received for general insurance. If insurers pass on the full rate increase to their customers, the impact on premiums would be an increase of only 3.5%.</p><p> </p><p>Tax forms only a small part of the cost of motor insurance. Other factors include competition, the volume of low value personal injury claims and fraud. The government has taken steps to crack down on the fraud and claims culture such as announcing at Autumn Statement 2015 proposals to end the right to cash compensation for minor whiplash injuries. The government expects the insurance industry to pass an average saving of £40 to £50 per motor insurance policy on to consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The government also encourages consumers to shop around for the most suitable cover at the best price.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-10T12:30:54.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450703/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450703/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Motor Vehicles: Insurance Premium Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the effect on motor insurance premiums of the recent increase in insurance premium tax.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","26009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450704","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-09","<p>Data on the number of domestic violence refuge places is not held centrally. It is for local areas to assess their needs for domestic abuse services and to make decisions on the provision of safe accommodation, including refuges and support for victims of domestic abuse.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-09T16:18:44.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450704/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450704/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Domestic Abuse: Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many domestic violence refuge places there were in (a) West Sussex and (b) Mid Sussex on 1 January (i) 2010 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","26004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450705","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department does not hold information centrally on the amount or type of land held by Community Land Trusts.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-09T16:19:08.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450705/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450705/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Community Land Trusts: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of brownfield sites in the West Sussex County Council area have been re-designated as community land trusts in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","26006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450706","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>It is not for the Department to estimate the amount of new build housing that will be bungalows. The National Planning Policy Framework and planning guidance requires local authorities to plan for a mix of housing based on current and future demographic trends, and the needs of different groups in their area.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T13:25:42.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450706/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450706/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made on the proportion of new build housing constructed in this Parliament that will be bungalows.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","25930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450707","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government has not ruled out applying to the EU Solidarity Fund. We are assessing the case for an application and will make a decision by the end of February. The European Union Solidarity Fund does not provide additional funding to local areas, but simply reimburses emergency costs that the Government would have incurred anyway. For this reason, the Government's immediate priority remains dealing with the urgent needs of those affected, which is why we have provided over £200 million to help those affected by the floods to support recovery and repair.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-09T16:18:20.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450707/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450707/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Floods: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to make a decision on whether to formally apply for EU Solidarity Funding to support communities affected by flooding in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450708","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-12","<p>Parliament approved the local government finance settlement for 2016-17 on 10 February. Recognising the particular costs of providing services in sparse rural areas, Rural Services Delivery Grant will increase by more than fivefold in 2016-17, to £80.5 million.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-12T12:50:17.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450708/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450708/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Local Government Finance: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to protect the rural services delivery grant.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450709","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department does not commission information relating to the closure of rural and urban libraries. Data relating to public libraries is collected and published annually by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy. My Rt Hon Friend will note that the number of library service points in the Wilshire Library Authority has increased from 34 in 2000, to 36 in 2015. Meanwhile, in Labour-run Wales, the number of library service points in the same period dropped from 321 to 274. <strong><br></strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>31 March</p></td><td><p>Total service points open ten hours or more per week, including mobile libraries, in England</p></td><td><p>Total service points open ten hours or more per week, including mobile libraries, in Wiltshire Library Authority</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2000</p></td><td><p>3,501</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2001</p></td><td><p>3,497</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002</p></td><td><p>3,504</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003</p></td><td><p>3,510</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004</p></td><td><p>3,524</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>3,474</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>3,494</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>3,469</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>3,451</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>3,428</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>3,393</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3,243</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3,181</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3,142</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3,076</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T13:47:34.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450709/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450709/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-04","Public Libraries: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) rural and (b) urban public libraries have closed in (i) Wiltshire and (ii) England in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450710","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-12","<p>The Tenancy Deposit Schemes provide monthly reports on service performance and six monthly statistical returns covering deposits accepted, the number of complaints received and the number of cases adjudicated upon. These reports are discussed quarterly with the Department.</p><p>The Tenancy Deposit Schemes in England are currently protecting over 3 million deposits on behalf of tenants, helping to raise standards in the private rented sector and ensuring that tenants are treated fairly at the end of the tenancy.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-12T12:51:16.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450710/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450710/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-04","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what metrics his Department uses to measure the effectiveness of deposit protection schemes.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450711","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>This is a matter for the independent telecoms regulator, Ofcom, who is currently reviewing the markets for digital communications in the UK and is due to report at the end of this month. Government has no role in this process.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-09T11:41:44.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450711/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450711/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-04","Openreach","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on which dates (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have met with BT to discuss separating Openreach from its parent company.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450712","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>By the end of phase two of the Superfast Broadband Programme approximately 95% of homes and businesses in West Sussex will have access to superfast broadband. For the Mid Sussex constituency over 96% of premises will have access to superfast broadband by the end of the project.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-09T13:46:06.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450712/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450712/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-04","Broadband: Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of small and medium-sized enterprises in (a) West Sussex and (b) Mid Sussex that will have access to superfast broadband by completion of phase two of the superfast broadband programme.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","26005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450713","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>Joint Force 2025 is about rebalancing our Armed Forces to strengthen the front line and maintain our military advantage. It will ensure that the Armed Forces are able to tackle a wider range of more sophisticated potential adversaries.</p><p>Joint Force 2025 will be able to deploy a larger force more quickly or undertake a large number of smaller operations simultaneously and will include enhanced Counter Terrorism capabilities; more fighter jet squadrons; new Protector armed remotely piloted aircraft; Maritime Patrol Aircraft; increased Carrier capability and readily deployable STRIKE brigades. Joint Force 2025 will also benefit from greater investment in new areas of capability such as cyber and space.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-09T16:29:46.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450713/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450713/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the additional capabilities the Joint Force 2025 will provide to the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","25869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450714","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>In order to help the French authorities we have jointly developed improved administrative procedures, whereby the UK is submitting Legion d'Honneur applications to the French in a steady flow in approximately the order they were received by the Ministry of Defence.</p><p>Some 2,900 applications have been sent to the French Embassy since the new system began in July last year; we have approximately 1,750 cases still to be submitted and the Department continues to receive new applications on a weekly basis. Cases are given priority on the grounds of ill-health or extreme age.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-11T16:32:58.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450714/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450714/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Veterans: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2015 to Question 10743, how many applications from Normandy veterans for the Legion d'Honneur are not yet processed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450715","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Global Coalition is making good progress against Daesh in Iraq. Over 30% of the territory that Daesh took in 2014 has been re-taken. The Iraqi security forces have substantially cleared Ramadi, the capital of Anbar province, and are working to make the area safe for displaced people to return. Further north, Kurdish forces have driven Daesh from the Sinjar area. In Syria, the Coalition is continuing to strike Daesh economic targets, including oilfields where we judge that recent strikes on its illicit oil industry have reduced Daesh's revenues by some 10%.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-10T16:42:08.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450715/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450715/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of recent progress of the international coalition to tackle Daesh.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","25887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450716","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-10","<p>Around 1,000 British personnel are directly contributing to the counter-Daesh coalition. RAF Tornado, Typhoon and Reaper aircraft are carrying out strike and reconnaissance missions against Daesh over Syria and Iraq, together with C130, Voyager and Sentinel aircraft. In Iraq, UK troops are also delivering counter-IED training to the Iraqi (including Kurdish) security forces together with other infantry skills, weapons maintenance and combat medical techniques as well as providing a key contribution at Coalition HQs throughout the region.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-02-10T16:43:01.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450716/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450716/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what contribution the armed forces are making to the international coalition to tackle Daesh.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","25888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450717","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>By 2025 we will have a highly capable expeditionary force of around 50,000. Joint Force 2025 will enable our Armed Forces to project power, deploy quickly and for longer periods and make the best use of new technology. We are investing in our front line by spending £178 billion over the next decade on equipment. We have committed to protecting the size of the Armed Forces by increasing the Royal Navy and Royal Air Force by a total of 700 personnel and not reducing the Army below 82,000.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-02-09T16:30:22.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450717/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450717/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the Strategic Defence and Security Review on the future size and power of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","25889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450718","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-11","<p>The number of Army personnel based in Army units located within Wiltshire as at 1 October 2015 is 13,010. The Army estimates that 9,900 entitled family members are currently associated with Army personnel based in Wiltshire.</p><p>The current planning assumption for the number of Army personnel based in Army units located within Wiltshire in 2020 is 17,700. It is estimated that 14,300 entitled family members will be associated with these Army personnel.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-02-11T16:25:11.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450718/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450718/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Army: Wiltshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many army (a) personnel and (b) dependents (i) are based and (ii) will be based in Wiltshire in 2020.","true","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450719","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government is committed to the convention that, before UK troops are committed to conflict, Parliament should have an opportunity to debate the matter, except when such action is necessary in an emergency. The Government will inform the House of any exceptional operation where there has not been prior debate in Parliament, as the Prime Minister did on 7 September 2015 in relation to the precision airstrike that took place on 21 August 2015.</p><p>The embedding of UK forces in the armed forces of allies is a valuable and commonplace activity governed through long standing and frequently reciprocal international arrangements. Although it is not policy for the House to be given the opportunity to debate their deployment we are committed to continued transparency about UK Service personnel embedded in other nations' armed forces on operations and I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement I made on 17 December 2015 (Official Report, column 97-98WS) which updated the House on this.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-02-09T17:53:41.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450719/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450719/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-04","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2016 to Question 23290, whether it is his policy for the House to be given an opportunity to debate in advance any decision to (a) launch airstrikes against ISIL/Daesh targets outside Syria and Iraq and (b) deploy UK military personnel, embedded within other nations' armed forces, on military operations against ISIL/Daesh targets outside Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","25918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450720","Department for Education","false","2016-02-12","<p>It is a criminal offence to operate an unregistered independent school. The Department for Education has recently published policy setting out our approach to prosecution which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulating-independent-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/regulating-independent-schools</a>.</p><p>We have also agreed additional resources for Ofsted to pursue cases.</p><p>The responsibility for ensuring that a child of compulsory school age receives a suitable full-time education rests with the child’s parents, either by the child’s attendance at a registered school or otherwise. ‘Otherwise’ can include education at home or attendance at settings which are not schools. If the local authority is not satisfied that a child is receiving suitable education, it has a duty to make a school attendance order.</p><p>Local authorities’ safeguarding duties apply wherever children are educated, whether in registered schools or elsewhere.</p><p>The Department also recently completed a call for evidence on proposals for the registration and inspection of out-of-school settings providing intensive education which were announced in the Counter-Extremism Strategy. Over 3,000 people completed the response form, either online or manually. The Department received a significant number of further representations to the consultation by email and post. All responses and representations are being logged, analysed and verified.</p><p>In line with Cabinet Office guidance, we will be publishing a response to the consultation in due course.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-12T12:50:59.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450720/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450720/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Out-of-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what safeguards are in place to ensure that unregistered schools meet appropriate standards of (a) educational provision and (b) safety.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","25874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450721","Department for Education","false","2016-02-09","<p>Foster carers will be able to access the existing 15 hour early education entitlement for three-and four-year olds for both their foster children and their own children. In addition, two year olds who are looked after by a local council or have left care under a special guardianship order, child arrangements order or adoption order are also entitled to 15 hours of early education.</p><p>Foster carers will be able to access the extended entitlement for three-and four-year olds for their own children provided that they meet the minimum income requirement. This means that foster parents should be earning the equivalent to 16 hours a week at National Minimum or Living Wage and their income should not exceed £100,000. This includes employed and self-employed parents.</p><p>Since foster carers are separately funded for the care of foster children, they will not be able to access the extended entitlement for their foster children. This is in line with the treatment of foster carers under Tax-Free Childcare, tax credits and Universal Credit.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-09T15:11:45.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450721/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450721/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many state registered foster carers her Department estimates will be eligible for the Government's proposed free 30 hours of childcare.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","25895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450722","Department for Education","false","2016-02-09","<p>Membership of the Child Protection Implementation Taskforce can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-announces-new-taskforce-to-transform-child-protection" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-announces-new-taskforce-to-transform-child-protection</a></p><p>Information relating to the proceedings of recent meetings of Implementation Taskforces is not disclosed as to do so could harm the frankness and candour of internal discussion.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-09T15:11:10.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450722/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450722/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Child Protection Taskforce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who sits on the Child Protection Task Force; and if she will publish dates and minutes of meetings of that body to date.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","25913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450723","Department for Education","false","2016-02-11","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my response to PQ 24570, submitted to Parliament on Thursday 4 February 2016, in which I explained that EBacc subjects are part of a broad and balanced curriculum and that there is space in the wider school curriculum to teach other subjects alongside the EBacc subjects.</p><p>On 3 November 2015 the Secretary of State for Education launched a public consultation seeking views on the government’s proposals for the implementation of the English Baccalaureate. The consultation closed on 29 January 2016 and the government response will be published in the spring.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-11T17:48:44.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450723/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450723/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Arts: English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24570, if she will make it her policy that creative subjects must be included in the new EBacc.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","25933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450724","Department for Education","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Park View Educational Trust formally sought for permission to employ teachers without qualified teacher status on 7 March 2013. This was granted on 15 March 2013.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-02-09T15:08:58.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450724/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450724/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Park View Educational Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2015 to Question 8250, when the three academies in the Park View Educational Trust (a) applied for and (b) were granted permission to employ teachers without qualified teacher status.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","25876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450725","Department for Education","false","2016-02-09","<p>The extended entitlement is intended to support working parents with the cost of childcare, enabling them to return to work or work additional hours if they wish to do so. Families where both parents work or one parent works in a single parent household will be eligible for these additional hours. In recognition of the particular challenges that paid carers can face in relation to childcare, the Childcare Bill allows for parents in certain circumstances to be regarded as being in work, for example, those parents who have caring responsibilities.</p><p>Households where one parent is working and one parent is being paid Carer’s Allowance or Universal Credit’s Carer Element will be able to access the extended entitlement provided the working parent meets the income eligibility requirements. This includes households where a parent is caring for their own three or four year old child where the child is in receipt of Disability Living Allowance or is certified blind.</p><p>In relation to single parents with a disabled child, where that parent meets the income eligibility requirements, they will also be able to access the extended entitlement. Parents who do not work will continue to receive Carer’s Allowance or Universal Credit.</p><p>It is also important to remember that all paid carers will be able to access the existing 15 hour early education entitlement for three and four year olds and the 15 hour early education entitlement for two year olds if they meet the eligibility criteria. More detail can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/help-with-childcare-costs/free-childcare-and-education-for-2-to-4-year-olds" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/help-with-childcare-costs/free-childcare-and-education-for-2-to-4-year-olds</a></p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of households with three or four year old children where one partner (or the sole parent in a lone parent family) meets the income eligibility criteria and is in receipt of benefits relating to caring responsibilities.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-09T15:15:50.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450725/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450725/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many paid carers her Department estimates will be eligible for the Government's proposed free 30 hours of childcare.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","25893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450726","Department for Education","false","2016-02-10","<p>Kinship carers will be able to access the existing 15 hour early education entitlement for any three and four year old children in their care. In addition, two year olds who are looked after by a local council or have left care under a special guardianship order, child arrangements order or adoption order are entitled to 15 hours per week of early education.</p><p>In respect of the extended entitlement for three and four year olds, kinship carers who have parental responsibility for the child will be able to access the extended entitlement provided that they are earning the equivalent to 16 hours a week at National Minimum or Living Wage and their income does not exceed £100,000. This includes employed and self-employed kinship carers.</p><p>The Department does not hold information on the number of kinship carers who would meet the income eligibility criteria and who have three or four year old children.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-10T16:27:22.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450726/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450726/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many kinship carers her Department estimates will be eligible for the Government's proposed free 30 hours of childcare.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","25894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450727","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-12","<p>Her Majesty’s Treasury (HMT) and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are developing plans to measure the success of Tax-Free Childcare (TFC) once it is in ‘steady state’ following the full rollout of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>We will measure how well TFC performs against its policy objective to help working families with their childcare costs. We will continue to engage with stakeholders as we start to put in place these plans.</p><p> </p><p>The key programmes for early education are the 15 hours of free childcare offered to all 3 and 4-year olds, and eligible 2-year olds. These provisions are measured under Assessment and Reporting Arrangements set out by the Standards and Testing Agency to ensure attainment against the Early Years Framework.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-12T13:59:08.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450727/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450727/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-04","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what metrics his Department plans to use to measure the effects of tax-free childcare on attainment in early years' education.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","25860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450728","Department for Education","false","2016-02-15","<p>Actions from the School Food Plan include significant lasting achievements, such as cooking in the national curriculum and the implementation of a set of new school food standards. We are committed to the Plan’s vision of increasing take-up of school meals through improvements to the quality of the food and the dining experience.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-02-15T15:04:03.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450728/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450728/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450728/answer/previousversion/45527","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","60","Education","Education","2016-02-04","School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has for the implementation of the recommendations in the School Food Plan (SFP) after the end of the SFP office's contract with her Department at the end of March 2016.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","25864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450729","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-09","<p>Energy suppliers participating in the Warm Home Discount this year (2015/16) have been given the voluntary option to provide a rebate to mobile home residents who meet the qualifying benefit as part of the Industry Initiatives section of the scheme. This scheme called the Park Homes Warm Home Discount pilot scheme is funded by obligated energy suppliers in the scheme and is open to permanent park home residents in England, Scotland or Wales. Residents on a Park Home site who pay for their electricity through their park site owner and meet one of the qualifying eligibility criteria can apply. If successful, residents will receive a one-off rebate of £140 towards their electricity bill.</p><p>The pilot scheme opened in November and is only open for a limited period and once a certain number of applications have been received and are successful, the pilot scheme will close. The pilot is currently expected to deliver just over 1000 rebates. This translates to just over £140,000 of support being delivered before the 31st March 2016.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","25904","2016-02-09T11:19:21.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450729/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450729/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Mobile Homes: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2016 to Question 22396, on park homes and the Warm Homes Discount, what the budget is for expenditure on the pilot scheme and what proportion is being funded by energy suppliers.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450730","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-09","<p>Energy suppliers participating in the Warm Home Discount this year (2015/16) have been given the voluntary option to provide a rebate to mobile home residents who meet the qualifying benefit as part of the Industry Initiatives section of the scheme. This scheme called the Park Homes Warm Home Discount pilot scheme is funded by obligated energy suppliers in the scheme and is open to permanent park home residents in England, Scotland or Wales. Residents on a Park Home site who pay for their electricity through their park site owner and meet one of the qualifying eligibility criteria can apply. If successful, residents will receive a one-off rebate of £140 towards their electricity bill.</p><p>The pilot scheme opened in November and is only open for a limited period and once a certain number of applications have been received and are successful, the pilot scheme will close. The pilot is currently expected to deliver just over 1000 rebates. This translates to just over £140,000 of support being delivered before the 31st March 2016.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","25903","2016-02-09T11:19:21.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450730/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450730/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Mobile Homes: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2016 to Question 22396, on park homes and the Warm Homes Discount, when that pilot scheme started; when that pilot scheme is expected to end; and what she plans the terms of eligibility for park home residents to apply to that pilot scheme will be.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450731","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-10","<p>Electricity sites are not determined by size, but are settled on their Profile Class. Licence conditions require energy suppliers to install smart meters (or in some circumstances, advanced meters) to all electricity sites in Profile Classes 1-4, and to gas sites where average annual consumption is below 732 MWh per year. We would expect most park home sites to fall into Profile Class 3 (Non-Domestic Unrestricted Customers) or 4 (Non-Domestic Economy 7 Customers).</p><p> </p><p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer I gave him on 18 January 2016 to Question 22397: park home owners of non-domestic sites have responsibility for any secondary metering equipment within their site and the decision to install smart meters for their tenants lies with them.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-10T11:18:44.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450731/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450731/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450731/answer/previousversion/44591","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Mobile Homes: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2016 to Question 22397, on park homes and smart meters, what the maximum size is of park home sites which fall within the definition of small non-domestic business sites for the roll-out of smart meters; and what steps are being taken to ensure that residents at such sites are offered a smart meter.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450732","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-11","<p>The load factor data used to calculate hydro generation tariffs were drawn from individual sites but then aggregated to calculate a load factor range on which to base the tariffs. This included data collected by external consultants and evidence submitted by various individuals and organisations, including the British Hydropower Association, in response to the consultation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-11T14:49:02.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450732/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450732/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450732/answer/previousversion/44590","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Hydroelectric Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how the response provided by the British Hydropower Association to her Department's Consultation on feed-in tariffs was taken into account by her Department in the assumptions used to determine that hydropower load factors are site specific.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","25851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450733","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government recognises the potential that tidal energy could play as part of the UK energy mix.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering how best we can support the development of tidal stream energy, following my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State’s autumn speech.</p><p> </p><p>On 10 February the Government announced that it will commission an independent review to assess the strategic case for tidal lagoons and whether they could represent good value for consumers. We anticipate that the review will be completed in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-11T15:27:26.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450733/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450733/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has for supporting the development of tidal energy projects.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","25945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450734","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-12","<p>In designating technologies in the less established group, we considered which technologies could have a significant long-term role in the UK energy mix, and where there remains significant potential for future cost reduction.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-12T14:21:03.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450734/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450734/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Electricity Generation: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what criteria her Department uses to designate technologies as less established for the purpose of Contract for Difference auctions.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","25946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450735","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-12","<p>As announced by the Secretary of State in her speech in November, the current intention is to hold the next CFD allocation round for ‘less established’ technologies (pot 2) in late 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We will set out details around future rounds in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-12T14:21:54.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450735/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450735/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-04","Electricity Generation: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she plans to publish further details of the next Contract for Difference auction; and which technologies she plans will be eligible for inclusion in that auction.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","25969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450736","Department of Health","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) has issued advice that Miracle Mineral Solution (MMS) is not safe and should not be sold as a supplement. It has been working with local authorities across the country to share knowledge, investigate and disrupt the sale of MMS and other similar products.</p><p> </p><p>Further activity is being conducted with the support of the Medicine and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and with the involvement of the FSA’s National Food Crime Unit. This activity is ongoing and it would not be appropriate to comment in detail.</p><p> </p><p>However, the FSA has secured the removal of MMS products from some major marketplace websites, and it has shared information internationally through the National Crime Agency, alerting authorities in other countries to planned seminars at which the use of MMS is promoted.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-02-09T16:18:56.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450736/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450736/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Miracle Mineral Solution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress the Food Standards Agency has made on coordinating steps in partnership with the Medicines and Health Products Regulatory Agency and the National Crime Agency to stop the marketing of Miracle Mineral Solution as a cure for children with autism; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","25937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450737","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-11","<p>My Department has no plans to commence paragraphs 35 and 36 of Schedule 23 of the Deregulation Act 2015, relating to the Breeding of Dogs Act 1973. While the option to do so remains, we believe that for the foreseeable future these records do have a role in assisting Local Authorities investigating welfare concerns at dog breeding establishments. This will mean that licensed dog breeders will therefore be required to continue keeping records in a prescribed form.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-11T10:57:01.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450737/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450737/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-04","Dogs: Animal Breeding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to commence the provisions of Schedule 23 of the Deregulation Act 2015 on the Breeding of Dogs Act 1973.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","25957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450738","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-11","<p>If a local flood group wish to progress a flood management scheme it should contact its local Environment Agency or the relevant county council or unitary authority for its area. Details for each local Environment Agency office can be obtained by email: <a href="mailto:enquiries@environment-agency.gov.uk" target="_blank">enquiries@environment-agency.gov.uk</a> or by telephone: Monday to Friday, 8am to 6pm 0370 8506 506.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-11T10:48:57.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450738/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450738/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-04","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what process local flood groups can apply for an allocation from the £2.3 billion of flood defence funding announced in the Comprehensive Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","25927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450739","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>I have been asked to reply.</p><p>The Department for International Development (DfID) provided £349 million in support of Palestinian development from 2011-15 and will provide a further £72 million in 2015-16, of which up to £25.5 million will be provided to the Palestinian Authority. This year, UK aid will support 36,000 children in primary education and support 270 enterprises to improve their annual sales or productivity.</p><p>UK aid is helping the Palestinian Authority to develop strong institutions, deliver essential public services and improve security – building the foundations for a sovereign and viable Palestinian state living alongside Israel in peace and security. For a breakdown on how financial assistance in the Palestinian Territories is spent, information is published on DfID’s Development Tracker website at <a href="https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://devtracker.dfid.gov.uk</a>.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-09T17:19:02.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450739/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450739/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what financial assistance his Department has given to the Palestinian Authority in each of the last five years for which information is available.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","25983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450740","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>We condemn all violence and all incitement to commit violence. We are concerned by reports of radicalisation, which may, in turn, encourage violence in the region. We have seen reports referring to Hamas. Hamas must renounce violence, recognise Israel and accept previously signed agreements. We have also received reports on the role school textbooks play in this area. An extensive study, conducted by a joint Israeli and Palestinian research team in 2013, found the need for textbooks on both sides to do far more to promote a more positive portrayal of each other, reflecting the principles of co-existence, tolerance, justice and human dignity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:23:42.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450740/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450740/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Palestinians: Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports his Department has received on the extent of radicalisation in the Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","25988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450741","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>We receive reports from our Embassy in Tel Aviv and our Consulate General in Jerusalem giving us regular updates on the current situation in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. These updates include reports on rockets being fired from the Gaza Strip into the sea; any rocket fire from Gaza into Israel; and any retaliatory Israeli air strikes on Gaza. According to reports, in December 2015 and January 2016 a total of three rockets were fired into Israel by Gazan militant groups.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T16:00:01.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450741/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450741/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports his Department has received on renewed rocket fire attacks into Gaza in Israel.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","26000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450742","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>We are deeply concerned by the recent violence in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. Since the start of the current violence, Ministers and officials have spoken regularly to both the Israeli government and the Palestinian Authority on the urgent need to de-escalate the tensions. We understand, and share, the deep frustration on all sides at the lack of progress on the Middle East Peace Process. The current violence underlines that a just and lasting resolution that ends the occupation and delivers peace for both Israelis and Palestinians is long overdue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:22:17.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450742/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450742/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on that region of recent violence in Israel and the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","25987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450743","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-12","<p>The advice against all but essential travel by air to or from Sharm el-Sheikh was issued by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office on 4 November 2015, and flights by UK carriers were suspended on the same day. Repatriation flights took place between 6–17 November 2015, supported by additional security measures.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working closely with the Egyptian authorities with a view to a resumption of flights as soon as possible, whereupon scheduling of such flights would be a matter for the airlines concerned.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-12T12:45:19.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450743/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-04","Egypt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to publish the listed dates for flights to Sharm el Sheikh airport on which his Department advised against all travel to the region.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450744","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>On 22 January I launched an online consultation seeking views on what form the national memorial to British victims of overseas terrorism should take (Official Report, 22 January 2016, col 47WS). The consultation is open until 4 March 2016. I have written to families of victims for whom the Government hold contact details. I have also issued an open letter available on gov.uk to invite all those with an interest to respond to the consultation should they wish to. Decisions on the memorial will be taken after we have fully considered responses to the consultation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-11T14:11:15.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450744/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450744/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Terrorism: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress the Government has made on the establishment of a memorial to UK citizens killed in terrorist attacks overseas; and what consultation the Government is undertaking with families of victims about that proposal.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","25873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450745","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>We currently fund projects through twelve Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories (including East Jerusalem); ten through the Conflict Stability and Security Fund and two through Bilateral Programme Budgets. All of these NGOs are registered as Israeli. We do not fund NGOs other than for specific projects that support Her Majesty's Government's objectives.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:19:41.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450745/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450745/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Middle East: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which (a) Israeli and (b) Palestinian non-governmental organisations and projects receiving funding from the Conflict Stability and Security Fund.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","25979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450746","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>Details on which non-governmental organisations and projects costs that have received Conflict Pool funding in each of the last five years are not held centrally and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T14:21:07.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450746/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450746/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Middle East: Conflict Pool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which (a) Israeli and (b) Palestinian non-governmental organisations and projects have received Conflict Pool funding in each of the last five years.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","25980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450747","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The UK strongly supports the Libyan Political Agreement (LPA) signed at Skhirat on 17 December by the majority of the Libyan delegates to the UN facilitated political dialogue, and by a wide range of representatives of Libyan society, municipal leaders and political parties. The Agreement paves the way for a Government of National Accord (GNA) and was unanimously endorsed by the UN Security Council Resolution 2259. Only a unified national government can begin the difficult work of establishing effective, legitimate governance, restoring stability and tackling the threat posed by Daesh. That is why we have been at the forefront of efforts to coordinate international support for the GNA.</p><p>The UK hosted a meeting with the UN and international donors and agencies in October to discuss plans for coordinated support from the international community to the GNA. This has been followed up through UN-hosted coordination meetings in Tunis. Two UK-funded advisors are already working closely with Libyan PM designate Fayez Serraj’s Presidency Council, and we stand ready to work with the international community to deliver a significant package of support to help a Government of National Accord to deliver a stable and prosperous future for all Libyan citizens. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) and I both spoke recently with PM designate Serraj and also with UN Special Representative Kobler to underline the UK’s continued support for the GNA process and UN efforts in this area. The Secretary of State plans to meet PM designate Serraj and House of Representatives President Agileh shortly to discuss what further support Britain can provide.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-09T15:48:03.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450747/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450747/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-04","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support the Government is providing to the government of Libya.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","25977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450748","Department of Health","false","2016-02-09","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guideline [CG133] regarding the longer-term management of self-harm in over eight’s sets out that care plans – including risk management and crisis plans – should be multidisciplinary and developed collaboratively with the person who self-harms and, provided the person agrees, with their family, carers or significant others. Care plans should also be shared with an individual’s general practitioner.</p><p> </p><p>It is for National Health Service organisations to design services to meet the needs of their local populations.</p><p> </p><p>NICE has produced a Clinical Knowledge Summary on the management of poisoning or overdose which is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://cks.nice.org.uk/poisoning-or-overdose#!scenario" target="_blank">http://cks.nice.org.uk/poisoning-or-overdose#!scenario</a></p><p> </p><p>This states that the person, if self-harm is found to be a factor, should have a psychiatric assessment by a trained professional.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Suicide Prevention Strategy also has details of what should be done if an overdose is suspected to be intentional. The Strategy acknowledges that emergency departments and primary care have important roles in the care of people who self-harm, with a focus on good communication and follow-up.</p><p> </p><p>In January, the Prime Minister announced £247 million to be used to develop further the provision of liaison psychiatry services in Emergency Departments in England. These services will ensure that people attending Emergency Departments who have mental ill health are assessed quickly and receive the most appropriate treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","25940 ; 25982","2016-02-09T16:12:58.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450748/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450748/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Drugs: Overdoses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to ensure that people who have been discharged from NHS hospitals after a medication overdose have (a) an in-depth assessment by a mental health nurse and (b) someone who will be at home with them.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","25981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450749","Department of Health","false","2016-02-09","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guideline [CG133] regarding the longer-term management of self-harm in over eight’s sets out that care plans – including risk management and crisis plans – should be multidisciplinary and developed collaboratively with the person who self-harms and, provided the person agrees, with their family, carers or significant others. Care plans should also be shared with an individual’s general practitioner.</p><p> </p><p>It is for National Health Service organisations to design services to meet the needs of their local populations.</p><p> </p><p>NICE has produced a Clinical Knowledge Summary on the management of poisoning or overdose which is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://cks.nice.org.uk/poisoning-or-overdose#!scenario" target="_blank">http://cks.nice.org.uk/poisoning-or-overdose#!scenario</a></p><p> </p><p>This states that the person, if self-harm is found to be a factor, should have a psychiatric assessment by a trained professional.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Suicide Prevention Strategy also has details of what should be done if an overdose is suspected to be intentional. The Strategy acknowledges that emergency departments and primary care have important roles in the care of people who self-harm, with a focus on good communication and follow-up.</p><p> </p><p>In January, the Prime Minister announced £247 million to be used to develop further the provision of liaison psychiatry services in Emergency Departments in England. These services will ensure that people attending Emergency Departments who have mental ill health are assessed quickly and receive the most appropriate treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","25940 ; 25981","2016-02-09T16:12:58.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450749/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450749/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Drugs: Overdoses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to ensure that NHS hospitals make referrals straight to crisis teams in cases where a patient has taken an overdose of medication.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","25982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450750","Department of Health","false","2016-02-12","<p>Information is not collected centrally on the number of three year olds who received a free NHS dental examination. Information is available for the number of courses of treatment for 0-17 year olds that contained a dental examination.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-12T10:17:49.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450750/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450750/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many three year olds received a free NHS dental check in (a) Nottingham North constituency, (b) Nottingham and (c) the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","25934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450751","Department of Health","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is committed to making the full £1.4 billion investment available over the course of this Parliament to improve mental health services for children and young people.</p><p> </p><p>In line with guidance published by NHS England, all clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have produced Local Transformation Plans (LTPs) for children and young people’s mental health and these have all now been assured and funding allocated for implementation. These plans required all key partners to agree locally how best to meet the mental health needs of children and young people in their local populations and should cover the whole spectrum of need, which includes improving access to mental health services for vulnerable groups such children in care and care leavers so that they can receive high quality mental health care when they need it. It is for local partners to decide how much of the funding which will be allocated to CCGs to improve local services throughout the five years will be spent specifically on children in care and other vulnerable groups. However, this will be based on an assessment of local needs and set out in the LTPs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s overall strategy to improve outcomes for care leavers is set out in the <em>Care Leaver Strategy: A cross-departmental strategy for young people leaving care</em> report (October 2013), and a one-year-on document, <em>Care Leaver Strategy: One year on progress update</em>, (October 2014) that reported on progress made and set out how the Government intends to further improve support for care leavers. The Government intends to publish its refreshed Care Leaver Strategy later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Government Association has produced a spreadsheet giving details of every LTP which can be found using the following webpage address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/camhs" target="_blank">www.local.gov.uk/camhs</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-10T14:52:04.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450751/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450751/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Mental Health Services: Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 11 January 2016 on £1.4 billion of funding for mental health services, what proportion of that funding will support children in care and care leavers.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","25867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450752","Department of Health","false","2016-02-09","<p>The information is not held in the format requested, however, figures for complaints received about mental health services in England, London and each London health trust in each year since 2010 are in the attached table.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-09T16:07:47.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450752/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450752/answer","PQ25881 table.xlsx","Mental health services written complaints","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450752/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many complaints were received about (a) adult and (b) children and adolescent mental health services in (i) England, (ii) London, (iii) each London borough and (iv) each London health trust in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","25881"
