"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450777","Department of Health","false","2016-02-09","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England (HEE) will be publishing the local plans as an appendix to the <em>HEE commissioning and investment plan – 2016/17</em> and will be published on the HEE website before the end of February 2016.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-02-09T13:53:24.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450777/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450777/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-04","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place in the Library copies of each Local Education and Training Board's workforce investment plan for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","26002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450778","Home Office","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Migration Advisory Committee (MAC) has not yet submitted its advice on whether nurses should remain on the Shortage Occupation List. The MAC will publish the report shortly after it is submitted to the Government. We will consider the findings carefully before making any final decision.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-09T15:18:13.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450778/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450778/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-04","Migrant Workers: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what evidence her Department has received from the Migration Advisory Committee on whether nurses should remain on the Government's Shortage Occupation List.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","26003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450779","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Government is committed to protecting the most vulnerable in society. One person without a home is one too many, which is why we will increase central investment over the next four years to £139 million for innovative programmes to prevent and reduce homelessness and rough sleeping.</p><p>We also want to help local authorities provide advice and assistance to those at risk of homelessness which is why we have protected the homelessness prevention funding for local authorities through the provisional local government finance settlement, totalling £315 million by 2019-20.</p><p>Decisions about frontline policing, and how resources are best deployed, are for Chief Constables and democratically accountable Police and Crime Commissioners. We have seen forces make significant changes to frontline policing to reflect the priorities of local people, including the most vulnerable. For example, several forces have established multi- agency teams to work collaboratively with other local public and voluntary sector services to tackle rough sleeping.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-23T17:20:56.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450779/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450779/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-04","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the police take to ensure the safety of people sleeping rough.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","25846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450780","Home Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>We expect all immigrants to the UK to abide by the law and to respect our shared values, and those who wish to stay permanently have to take the Knowledge of Life in the UK Test which reinforces this expectation. For those that do not respect the law, we will consider removal and exclusion. We keep all our immigration polices under regular review.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-11T14:52:02.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450780/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450780/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-04","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policies of the events in Cologne at New Year 2015-16 in respect of information given to new immigrants to the UK on legal and cultural issues.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","25847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450781","Attorney General","false","2016-02-09","<p>The way in which the Criminal Justice System investigates and prosecutes rape allegations is changing and the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is taking a leading role. In September 2015 the CPS and Police set up a joint National Rape Steering Group, supported by a joint Delivery Board, to drive forward a co-ordinated programme of work. This programme includes the development of an optimum model for working (in rape and serious sexual offence cases) between the CPS and the Police which will address early investigative advice and file quality.</p><p>It is a CPS priority that its staff have the tools and skills necessary to prosecute effectively. A detailed CPS/Police Joint National Rape Action Plan was published in June 2014 which identified a programme of training activity to deliver improvements in investigation and prosecution outcomes. This extensive programme, consisting of a range of face to face specialist training measures, is currently underway.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-09T15:45:38.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450781/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450781/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-04","Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps his Department plans to take in response to the recommendations in the report by HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate, entitled Thematic Review of the CPS Rape and Serious Sexual Offences Units, published in February 2016, (a) that a new protocol should be developed with each police force capturing early investigative advice and file quality and (b) in respect of training for lawyers and paralegal staff.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","25920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450782","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-09","<p>The UK Government works closely with African and other countries to promote the conservation of the world's wildlife, including through galvanising action to end the illegal trade in ivory.</p><p> </p><p>We hosted the London Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade in February 2014, and supported the Government of Botswana in its hosting of a follow-up Conference in March 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The UK actively supports the African-led Elephant Protection Initiative, launched in the margins of the London Conference, which now has eleven African countries as members. We have committed over £1 million to this initiative over the last two years.</p><p> </p><p>Defra’s Illegal Wildlife Trade Challenge Fund has made grants to 19 projects in its first round, including eight projects in Africa, worth £2.1 million, tackling the ivory trade. Projects to be funded under a second round will be announced shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is also providing training in counter-poaching activity in Gabon, through the Ministry of Defence, and has provided support for judicial capacity building in skills related to tackling the illegal trade in wildlife products in Kenya and Tanzania.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-09T16:06:31.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450782/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450782/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-04","Africa: Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support the Government (a) has provided and (b) plans to provide to governments in Africa for eradicating the killing of animals for the ivory trade.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","25875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450783","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-11","<p>As set out in DFID’s settlement letter from HM Treasury, over the Spending Review period, DFID plans to transfer the amounts referred to in table 2.7 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 to the following government departments and cross-government funds:</p><p> </p><p>Conflict, Stability &amp; Security Fund</p><p>Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills</p><p>Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport</p><p>Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change</p><p>Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs</p><p>Department of Health</p><p>Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office</p><p>Her Majesty’s Revenue &amp; Customs</p><p>Home Office</p><p>Office for National Statistics</p><p>Prosperity Fund</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-11T14:36:44.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450783/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450783/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-04","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24173 between 2015-16 and 2019-20, to which other government departments and cross-government funds her Department plans to transfer, the amounts referred to in table 2.7 on page 85 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Phillips","Sleaford and North Hykeham","Stephen Phillips","25964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450784","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The MoJ determines that information is commercially sensitive including when documents contain information that if released, would be likely to prejudice someone’s commercial interests. The Ministry of Justice has robust contract management processes aligned with National Audit Office Guidelines and will manage the plan strictly in accordance with the contract.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T18:00:17.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450784/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450784/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answers of 2 February 2016 to Questions 23949 and 24848, for what reasons the action plans and operational assurance audit referred to are commercially sensitive.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","25941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450785","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-11T14:36:56.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450785/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450785/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Legal Aid Scheme: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Written Statement of 28 January 2016, WS499, how much the Government spent on work on the criminal legal aid tendering process before deciding not to go ahead with that process.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","26013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450786","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>Judicial training is a judicial matter and fulfilled by the Judicial College, which reports to the Lord Chief Justice. Training for barristers is a matter for their own professional bodies.</p><p> </p><p>The Judicial College have advised me that a workshop on the cross examination of vulnerable witnesses is incorporated into their Serious Sexual Offences Seminar. This is mandatory training for all judges who have been authorised to hear cases involving serious sexual offences.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-11T14:23:57.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450786/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450786/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Witnesses: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what training is available for judges and barristers to assist them when questioning child witnesses in cases involving sexual offences.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","25947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450787","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government position remains that a retirement age of 70 for all judicial office holders is appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>A mandatory retirement age of 70 means both judges and magistrates can continue to make a contribution to society whilst allowing for regular recruitment of the judiciary.</p><p> </p><p>It also enables the judiciary to have the correct number of judges and magistrates, while preventing them from retiring on an ad hoc basis, and ensuring judicial independence is protected.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-09T17:51:59.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450787/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450787/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Magistrates: Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential costs and benefits of reducing the mandatory retirement age of magistrates from 70 to 60; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450788","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Every death in custody is a tragedy and we work hard to learn the lessons from each death. All deaths in prison custody are subject to a police investigation, an independent investigation by the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman (PPO) and a Coroner’s inquest.</p><p> </p><p>I can confirm that each of these processes has begun following the death of Ms Reed, and I extend my condolences to her family and friends. Until investigations have concluded it would not be appropriate for me to comment further.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T15:01:13.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450788/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450788/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Sarah Reed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the status is of (a) the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman and (b) any other investigation into the death in custody of HM Prison Holloway prisoner Sarah Reed who was pronounced dead on 11 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450789","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>The information requested can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T15:05:37.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450789/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450789/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Police: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many police officers have been convicted of an assault committed while on duty in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450790","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>My Department takes the issue of security within courts extremely seriously. Working with our security suppliers, officials continue to analyse the data within the other category to ensure the data provided answers question 18874 and provides detail on “other weapons” as requested.</p><p> </p><p>I will write a letter to honourable member soon and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-09T17:55:45.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450790/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450790/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Courts: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 18874, when his Department plans to write to clarify the date captured in the other category; and if he will place a copy of that letter in the Libraries of both Houses.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450791","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer which I gave in PQ 25197 to George Howarth on 9<sup>th</sup> February 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-09T16:37:00.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450791/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450791/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to announce the level of grant funding available to Police and Crime Commissioners for commissioning support services for victims of crime; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","25908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450792","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>We will always have enough prison places for those sent to us by the courts and will do so in a way that gives taxpayers the best possible value for money.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to re-activate police cells under Operation Safeguard. No police cells have been used under Operation Safeguard since October 2008. This means the number of prisoners held temporarily overnight in police cells has fallen from over 50,000 in 2008.</p><p> </p><p>Tables 1 and 2 show the number of prisoners, by the requested age groups, who were temporarily held overnight in police cells in England and Wales each month in 2014 and 2015. No prisoners aged 15 to 17 were held overnight in police cells in 2014 and 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: 18 year olds and above during 2014</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Total number of prisoners held in police cell</p></td><td><p>18 to 20 year olds</p></td><td><p>21 and over</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan – 14</p></td><td><p>168</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>164</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feb – 14</p></td><td><p>372</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>359</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mar – 14</p></td><td><p>175</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>168</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr – 14</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>58</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May – 14</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>44</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun – 14</p></td><td><p>112</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jul – 14</p></td><td><p>274</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>266</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aug – 14</p></td><td><p>116</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>107</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept – 14</p></td><td><p>62</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oct – 14</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov – 14</p></td><td><p>149</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>140</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dec - 14</p></td><td><p>111</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>106</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2: 18 year olds and above during 2015</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Total number of prisoners held in police cell</p></td><td><p>18 to 20 year olds</p></td><td><p>21 and Over</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan – 15</p></td><td><p>89</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>87</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feb – 15</p></td><td><p>112</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>111</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mar – 15</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr – 15</p></td><td><p>107</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>102</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May - 15</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun – 15</p></td><td><p>113</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jul – 15</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>173</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aug – 15</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sept – 15</p></td><td><p>137</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oct – 15</p></td><td><p>174</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>170</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov – 15</p></td><td><p>195</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dec - 15</p></td><td><p>151</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>148</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-09T17:19:49.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450792/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450792/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-04","Prisoners: Police Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2016 to Question 23552, how many times police cells were used to hold prisoners overnight who were aged (a) 15 to 17, (b) 18 to 20 and (c) 21 and over in each month in 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450793","Prime Minister","false","2016-02-09","<p>We have been very clear: we are proud that Britain is one of the most successful multi ethnic, multi faith democracies in the world. The Government is clear that people have full freedom here to choose and practice their faith. It is right though to challenge the view held by some that we should encourage communities to develop separately and effectively live in a segregated way. The Government is committed to boosting integration in some of our most isolated communities, and to proudly promoting the British values that we all share.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-02-09T17:12:21.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450793/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450793/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-02-04","Race Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether it is Government policy to promote multiculturalism in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","25914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450794","Prime Minister","false","2016-02-09","<p>The figures were taken from analysis carried out by DWP and HMRC on benefit and Tax Credit claims by recently arrived EEA migrants.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-02-09T17:13:33.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450794/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450794/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-02-04","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to his oral contribution of 3 February 2016, Official Report, column 939, what the source is of the statistics he quoted.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","25906"
