"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450260","Home Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Home Office does not centrally record the number of people accommodated in temporary dispersal accommodation each month and such information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-10T13:30:47.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450260/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450260/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450260/answer/previousversion/44039","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-03","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been accommodated in temporary dispersal accommodation under a contract with Compass for the provision of asylum accommodation in each Compass region in each month since April 2015.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","25594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450261","Home Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government has determined that the principles of the Ombudsman’s decision in the Milne v Government Actuary’s Department case should be applied to other affected individuals, including retired firefighters and police officers in England.</p><p>Redress will be paid to affected individuals via their relevant pension scheme, and we will be providing fire and rescue authorities and police forces with necessary grant to cover the cost of these payments.</p><p>Pension administrators will have now completed the majority of calculations and the majority of payments to individuals will be made by April 2016. This does not preclude payments being made earlier in many cases. I trust that authorities will make payments as soon as is practical and understand that some have already done so.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-08T16:20:35.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450261/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450261/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-03","Fire Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress her Department has made on implementing the recommendations of the Government Actuaries Department relating to firefighters' pensions in its report dated 28 August 2015.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","25614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450262","Home Office","false","2016-02-10","<p>We do not hold the information requested centrally and providing it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-10T13:35:01.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450262/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450262/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-03","Deportation: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many EU citizens who have not started working have been deported after six months to which countries since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Philp","Croydon South","Chris Philp","25687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450263","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-10","<p>The UK government is concerned by the increase in demolitions of properties in Area C of the West Bank which are harmful to peace, and continues to raise this with Israeli authorities. According to OCHA, at least 21 of the 23 structures demolished on 2<sup>nd</sup> February in the South Hebron Hills had been funded by international donors. We are awaiting confirmation from OCHA, however we understand 10 of these structures were funded by the EU.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-10T13:17:40.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450263/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450263/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-03","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether any of the structures destroyed by the Israeli authorities in the South Hebron Hills on 2 February 2016 were fully or part-funded by the Government; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450264","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-08","<p>The United Kingdom remains fully committed to global polio eradication and has pledged £300 million to support the Global Polio Eradication Initiative for 2013 to 2019. Of the £300 million, £270 million is directed to the World Health Organisation, which hosts the Global Polio Eradication Initiative. £30 million is allocated to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, to support its role in the global introduction of the Inactivated Polio Vaccine, a key step in the path to eradication.</p><p>As the third largest contributor towards global polio eradication, UK support has played a crucial role in the more than 99% decrease in polio cases since the launch of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative in 1988.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-08T16:47:25.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450264/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450264/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-03","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what programmes her Department has contributed to from the £300 million it allocated to eradicate polio.","true","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","25644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450265","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>The average clearance time of employment tribunal claims for non-payment of the National Minimum Wage<sup>1</sup> in each of the last five years is as shown in Table 1 below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Average time in weeks</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>source: ET Database February 2016</p><p><sup>1</sup> &quot;Suffer a detriment and/or dismissal related to failure to pay the minimum wage or allow access to records&quot;</p><p> </p><p>In 2014-15 we reviewed outstanding cases and removed a backlog of very old cases from the case management system. The overall trend in average clearance time for single cases is improving and this can be seen in the Published Statistics at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-02-11T13:42:53.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450265/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450265/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time of cases in employment tribunals related to non-payment of the National Minimum Wage was in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","25609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450266","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>The information requested is commercially sensitive. It is normal Government practice not to release commercially sensitive information.</p><p> </p><p>The use of action plans is part of an ongoing standard contract management process used routinely with all 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) to promptly and proactively address issues which have been identified.</p><p> </p><p>We have robust contract management in place to monitor these plans, including commercial and financial specialists to ensure that providers deliver effective services and value for money. Robust performance management systems and audit arrangements are in place to manage the contracts. This approach is in line with National Audit Office contract management standards.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25619","2016-02-10T17:53:03.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450266/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450266/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 24848, on the South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company, what areas of that company's activities the action plan referred to covers; in what way his Department plans to monitor the implementation of that plan; and what steps his Department can take if a community rehabilitation company fails to implement such a plan in the agreed timescale.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","25618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450267","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>The information requested is commercially sensitive. It is normal Government practice not to release commercially sensitive information.</p><p> </p><p>The use of action plans is part of an ongoing standard contract management process used routinely with all 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) to promptly and proactively address issues which have been identified.</p><p> </p><p>We have robust contract management in place to monitor these plans, including commercial and financial specialists to ensure that providers deliver effective services and value for money. Robust performance management systems and audit arrangements are in place to manage the contracts. This approach is in line with National Audit Office contract management standards.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25618","2016-02-10T17:53:03.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450267/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450267/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2016 to Question 23948, what the names are of the seven community rehabilitation companies referred to.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","25619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450268","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-08","<p>We have a range of security measures and searching techniques to prevent smuggling into prisons and to detect items of contraband including drugs. We have legislated to make smuggling New Psychoactive Substances (NPS) into prison illegal, use specially trained dogs to detect illicit drugs and will evaluate the use of Body Scanners to reveal drugs concealed within the body.</p><p> </p><p>We refer all visitors to prisons found in possession of drugs to the police. We also use closed visits, where the prisoner and visitor are prevented from physical contact, to deal with visitors and prisoners who smuggle or are suspected of conveying drugs through visits.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number and type of drugs confiscated from visitors in each prison for the period 01 October 2015 to 31 December 2015. Prior to 01 October 2015 the Incident Reporting System (IRS) did not specifically record who possessed the drugs found.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Number of incidents where drugs were found in visitor's possession, October to December 2015, by establishment and drug type</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Establishment</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Drug type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of incidents<sup>12</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aylesbury</p></td><td><p>Cannabis</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Birmingham</p></td><td><p>NPS: Black Mamba</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brinsford</p></td><td><p>Cannabis</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bristol</p></td><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bullingdon</p></td><td><p>NPS: Spice</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cardiff</p></td><td><p>Amphetamines</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Buprenorphine/Subutex</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr