"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450269","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-09","<p>Data on the number of motor accidents between 2006 and 2015 was obtained from publicly available datasets published by the Department for Transport. This data can be obtained from:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/497176/ras45004.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/497176/ras45004.xls</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/461863/ras10013.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/461863/ras10013.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-09T15:56:22.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450269/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450269/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2016 to Question 20722, what figures his Department used for the number of motor accidents in each year from 2006 to 2015 in formulating that Answer.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","25612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450270","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-08","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25592 ; 25743","2016-02-08T16:33:24.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450270/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450270/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Prisons: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many weapons of which type have been confiscated from visitors to prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450271","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-10","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-02-10T13:28:39.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450271/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450271/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Death: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many inquests have taken place related to the death of UK citizens whilst at sea in each year including and since 2010.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","25576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450272","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-11","<p>There are more than 500 specially trained dogs used within prisons to search prisoners, visitors, prison perimeters and suspicious packages for illicit items, such as drugs, weapons, alcohol and mobile phones. Many dogs are trained so that they can detect a range of contraband rather than one particular substance. The specific combination of capabilities is managed by regional search teams so that dogs can be used most effectively to tackle prevalent risks in that region.</p><p> </p><p>For those reasons, it is not possible to allocate a specific budget to dogs who have been trained to detect alcohol. Data on the number of alcohol finds made by dogs is not recorded.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-11T14:44:31.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450272/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450272/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","National Offender Management Service: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the National Offender Management Service's budget was for its allocation of illicit alcohol-detecting dogs in each of the last five years; and how many finds have been made by those dogs in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450273","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-08","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","25591 ; 25743","2016-02-08T16:33:24.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450273/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450273/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-03","Prisons: Knives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times (a) knife, (b), shiv, (c) shank, (d) chib and (e) another slang word for a blade were recorded on the Incident Report System in each prison since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","25592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450274","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>For fatalities in construction (Standard Industrial Classification, section F) reported to HSE between 2005/06 and 2014/15, the average time between the date of incident and the date prosecution action was approved is 751 days. This number does not include some more recent or complex incidents, which remain under investigation. The time between the incident and prosecution approved to date by yearly time bands is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Time between incident and approval</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>0 - 1 year</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1-2 years</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2-3 years</p></td><td><p>56</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3-4 years</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4-5 years</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>5 years +</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>189</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-09T13:31:58.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450274/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450274/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Construction: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time taken was between a fatal accident occurring in construction and the start of a prosecution on the latest date for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","25567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450275","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-11","<p>For fatalities in construction (Standard Industrial Classification Section F) resulting in a prosecution approval by HSE between 2010/11 and 2014/15, the average time between the date of incident and the date prosecution action was approved in each year is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year of approval</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average number of days between incident and prosecution approval by HSE</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>877</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>841</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>783</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>851</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p>879</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-11T13:29:26.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450275/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450275/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Construction: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what change there has been in the length of time between a fatal accident and a prosecution over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","25568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450276","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>The percentage of construction (Standard Industrial Classification, section F) prosecutions completed in the relevant year and resulting in a conviction in each of the last five years, is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cases for which legal proceedings have been instituted</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Convictions</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage resulting in conviction</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>218</p></td><td><p>201</p></td><td><p>92%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>241</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>91%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>209</p></td><td><p>95%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14r</strong></p></td><td><p>225</p></td><td><p>209</p></td><td><p>93%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15p</strong></p></td><td><p>258</p></td><td><p>243</p></td><td><p>94%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>p - provisional</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>r - revised</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-09T13:27:53.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450276/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450276/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Construction: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of construction prosecutions has resulted in a conviction in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","25569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450277","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>The percentage of construction (Standard Industrial Classification, section F) fatalities resulting in at least one prosecution being approved to date in each of the last eight years is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Number of Fatalities in Construction reported to HSE</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of fatalities with approved prosecution action*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007/2008</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>74</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>51%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008/2009</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>57</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>49%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009/2010</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>44</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>45%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/2011</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>52</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/2012</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>49</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>45%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/2013</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>46</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/2014</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>47</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/2015</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>39p</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>p - Data published for the most recent year is given a 'p' status (provisional), and a year later is released as final.</p><p> </p><p>*Investigations of some recent and more complex incidents are continuing.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-09T16:10:40.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450277/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450277/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Construction: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of construction fatalities has resulted in at least one prosecution in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","25570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450278","Scotland Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>As the hon Member knows from our discussions on this issue, Scotland Office Ministers have taken a close interest in this matter, including meeting with BIS Ministers to discuss the impact of Tata Steel closures in Scotland. While Scotland Office Ministers have not attended the Taskforce, the Scotland Office has been represented by officials at all of the Scottish Steel Taskforce meetings to date.</p><p>In addition, we have worked with BIS colleagues to ensure that Scottish Government officials have been able to fully participate in the three UK working groups, and Scottish Government have been invited to be part of the newly formed Steel Council.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-02-11T12:02:25.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450278/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450278/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-02-03","Scottish Steel Task Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department attended the Scottish Steel Task Force meeting on (i) 29 January 2015, (ii) 13 November 2015, (iii) 26 November 2015, (iv) 11 December 2015 and (v) 14 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","25595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450280","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold statistics on the number of UK citizens who die at sea, become missing persons or are the victims of sexual assault or serious crimes against the person whilst at sea.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-09T17:08:31.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450280/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450280/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) deaths, (b) missing persons incidents and (c) sexual assaults or serious crimes against the person have been reported against UK citizens whilst at sea in each year since and including 2010.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","25575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450281","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-10","<p>Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) has a Committed Obligation to deliver proposals with an acceptable business case for Oyster Pay As You Go (PAYG) and contactless payment (CPAY) to five stations and their respective Lines of Route; this obligation includes Radlett.</p><p> </p><p>The works needed to complete this obligation are technically complex and require a substantial amount of work by Transport for London (TfL) - including a significant upgrade to the Oyster back office which will not be complete before 2017 - before they can be introduced.</p><p> </p><p>GTR, TfL and DfT officials meet at a Project Board every month to review progress.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-10T16:11:31.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450281/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450281/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Public Transport: Radlett","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking on ensuring the extension of the Oyster card pay as you go system to Radlett.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","25620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450282","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Department for Transport is preparing a revised Accessibility Action Plan (AAP) at the moment in discussion with the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee. We plan for the AAP to be ready for wider consultation in the summer and that it will likely be published by the end of the year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-09T15:52:18.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450282/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450282/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450282/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 18454, what progress his Department is making on updating the Accessibility Action Plan; and when he plans to publish it.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","25624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450283","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to my previous answer of 11 January 2016 <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=20671" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=20671</a>.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-09T16:13:45.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450283/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450283/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","British Transport Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has requested the British Transport Police to set out options for a reduction in the British Transport Police budget.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","25577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450284","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-08","<p>I am intending to discuss with the Scottish Minister about the experience of the lower limit in Scotland and about the timescales to get access to robust evidence of the road safety impact. It is important to base our decisions on evidence and the Scottish experience will be crucial to that before we consider any possible changes to the limits in England and Wales. This Government’s current position however remains to focus resources on enforcing against the most serious offenders.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-08T13:56:08.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450284/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450284/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450284/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Driving under Influence: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Scottish Government on the results of that government's lowering of drink-drive limits; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450285","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-08","<p>The invitation to tender for the Seafarer Projections Review was sent out by the Crown Commercial Service on Tuesday 19 January 2016 and the closing date for bids is Tuesday 1 March 2016. Part of the ITT specified that the research should include a model and projections for seafarers over the next decade. We will draw upon this research when developing our own projections. Subject to the tender process, it is our intention to publish this work when it is complete.</p><p> </p><p>In Seafarer Statistics 2015, published on 27 January 2016, it was mentioned that in 2016, the department will be undertaking a user engagement exercise to find out more about how the Seafarer Statistics are used and to collate views on the methodology. The aim of this will be to identify any opportunity for methodological improvements and ensure that the statistics continue to be fit for purpose. The inclusion of projections within this annual publication will be considered as part of this review.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the honourable Member to my response to the Hon Member for Easington (Graeme Morris) on 27 January 2016 <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=23191" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=23191</a>; and to my answers to the Hon Member 24914 https://wqa.parliament.uk/Questions/Details/31981 and 24917 https://wqa.parliament.uk/Questions/Details/31978.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-08T14:25:26.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450285/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450285/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450285/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Shipping: Crew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to ensure that his Department's annual seafarer statistics include forecasts of future numbers of UK seafarers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450286","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-08","<p>The department is currently seeking evidence on possible cases of discrimination, including on pay discrimination, through the Post Implementation Review of the Equality Act 2010 (Work on Ships and Hovercraft) Regulations 2011 which is due to complete in autumn 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-08T15:14:06.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450286/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450286/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Shipping: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the extent of the practice of nationality-based pay discrimination against non-EEA seafarers employed on (a) UK and (b) non-UK registered vessels working from UK ports.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450287","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-09","<p>None of the revenues relate to fines for poor performance paid to the Department as no fines were levied.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-09T16:31:44.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450287/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450287/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-03","Southern","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23955, how much of those revenues were directed to his Department as fines for poor performance.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","25686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450288","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>DWP has conducted a consultation to seek views on how support can best be provided to help meet the costs of disability faced by people who are currently awarded points due to aids and appliances. The department has received responses from a range of interested parties, including disabled people and disability organisations. The consultation has now closed and the department is considering these responses.</p><p>No decision has yet been made as to whether any change should be made to the current system and the department does not have any preference between the five options presented in the consultation. We also invited additional suggestions for change.</p><p>If the department decides that change is required, a full equality analysis will be conducted and considered prior to a final decision being made, in line with the Department’s obligations under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-09T10:04:29.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450288/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450288/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department carried out on the changes proposed in the Consultation on aids and appliances and the daily living component of personal independence payment, Cm 9171, published in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","25556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450289","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-11","<p>DWP operates a national network of contact centres which allows calls from anywhere in the country to be routed to the next available agent, regardless of their location. This virtual national telephony network means that it is impossible to provide a definitive answer regarding the volume of calls received from any particular geographical area.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-11T13:25:34.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450289/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450289/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450289/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Social Security Benefits: Inverclyde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many telephone calls his Department received to its benefit helplines from people in Inverclyde in 2015.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","25557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450290","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-09","<p>Universal Credit gives greater incentives for people to move into, and then progress in work. Within legacy benefits single young people under 25 without children are not generally eligible for in-work support from Working Tax Credit and can face a severe withdrawal of benefits when they go into work. The introduction of Universal Credit represents a marked improvement in support.</p><p>Furthermore, DWP is introducing a new Youth Obligation from April 2017 which will ensure that young people aged 18–21 who are claiming Universal Credit, are given the support, skills and experience they need to move into work, to sustain work and to fulfil their potential.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-09T14:05:15.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450290/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450290/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Universal Credit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he plans to take to support unemployed young people under 25 whose income will be affected by the planned changes to universal credit from April 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","25663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-08","<p>Figures published by ONS show that rising employment in the West Midlands since 2010 – reflected in falling unemployment – has been dominated by more people in full-time and permanent jobs.</p><p>Information on trends in zero-hours contracts over this period is not available on a consistent basis. This reflects the view of the Office for National Statistics (ONS) that responses to questions about zero-hours contracts in the Labour Force Survey are likely to have been affected by greater awareness of the term itself.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-08T16:23:01.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450291/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-03","Unemployment: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the correlation between the reduction in the rate of unemployment in the West Midlands between 2010 and 2016 and any trend in the number of people employed on zero-hour contracts in that region.","true","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","25638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450292","Attorney General","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service routinely provides the Law Officers with updates on cases and casework issues. In accordance with the practice adopted by previous Law Officers I do not usually comment on which individual cases are raised with me.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-09T15:40:33.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450292/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450292/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-03","Rendition and Torture: Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether he has been consulted by the Crown Prosecution Service about a charging decision in Operation Lydd.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","25717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450293","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The attached table shows the amount of funding for adult skills allocated in 2016-17 and indicative allocations for 2017-18 to 2019-20 for apprenticeship and non-apprenticeship provision. These figures are taken from the Skills Funding Letter 2016-17 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/skills-funding-letter-april-2016-to-march-2017" target="_blank">Skills funding letter: April 2016 to March 2017 - Publications - GOV.UK</a>.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-29T09:56:51.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450293/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450293/answer","Attachment to 25735.docx","Funding for adult skills","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450293/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","Adult Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Skills of 2 February 2016, Official Report, column 764, what proportion and amount of funding for adult skills is planned to be allocated to (a) apprenticeship provision and (b) non-apprenticeship provision in (i) 2016-17, (ii) 2017-18, (iii) 2018-19 and (iv) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","25735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450294","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>I refer to my answer of 25 January.</p><p> </p><p>I have asked my officials as a first step to request an urgent update from Trading Standards on their recent market surveillance activities. I am aware that Leicester Trading Standards recently seized 1,500 unsafe laser pens at point of entry and the importer agreed to destroy them.</p><p> </p><p>In addition RAPEX (the European electronic notification platform for the notifying and removal of dangerous consumer products) statistics show 98 different types of laser pointers were removed from the EU market and of these 9 different products were notified by UK market surveillance authorities.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T17:58:05.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450294/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450294/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2016 to Question 23018, what steps he is taking to limit the availability of laser pens.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","25699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450295","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>Consumer products such as laser pens intended for use by consumers are regulated under The General Product Safety Regulations 2005. BIS is responsible for the legislation but it is enforced by Local Authority Trading Standards Services.</p><p> </p><p>Under the rules, Trading Standards Officers have a range of powers available to them with regards enforcement of the legislation such as requirements to mark or to warn, or to issue withdrawal or recall notices. They also have the power to prosecute traders.</p><p> </p><p>This is a well-established regime that has seen many hundreds of dangerous products taken off the market including laser pens.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T17:57:05.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450295/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450295/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","General Product Safety Regulations 2005","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2016 to Question 23018, what steps he is taking to enforce the General Product Safety Regulations 2005.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","25700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450296","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>I refer to my answer of 25 January.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Consumer Protection Act 1987 and the General Product Safety Regulations, a business importing into the EU/EEA must have a representative within the EU/EEA who is responsible and liable for the safety of imported goods. This enables Customs and Trading Standards to check that imported laser products comply with safety standards. It is harder for them to carry out these checks where customers order goods from a company outside the EU and receive them directly through the post.</p><p> </p><p>We therefore advise customers who want to buy laser products to go to a reputable dealer with authorised representation in the European Union. If consumers are concerned about the safety of laser products on sale they should report the website or retailer to their local Trading Standards department.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-11T17:59:13.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450296/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450296/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","Lasers: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2016 to Question 23018, on lasers: regulation, what steps he is taking to restrict direct sale into the UK to individual customers.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","25701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450297","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Skills Funding Agency, one of the partner organisations of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, has secured approximately £725,624,976 including administration costs from the European Social Fund (ESF) on behalf of 38 Local Enterprise Partnership areas. The Skills Funding Agency is currently procuring learning and skills activity identified by local areas. These funds are profiled to be spent by end March 2018.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-08T15:28:01.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450297/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450297/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","European Social Fund: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much of the funding under the European Social Fund programme assigned to his Department he expects to allocate in the current funding round.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","25741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450298","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Management fees are a matter between lead contractors and sub-contractors. For European Social Fund (ESF) contracts procured by the Skills Funding Agency, the ESF and 2015/2016 match funding rules state that “You must publish your supply-chain fees and charges policy on your website before entering into any subcontracting agreements for the 2015 to 2016 funding year.” This must include the typical percentage range of fees a contractor retains to manage subcontractors, and how this range is calculated.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-08T16:10:13.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450298/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450298/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","European Social Fund: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has regulations in place to limit top-sliced management fees for European Social Fund funding by lead contractors to sub-contractors.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","25742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450299","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS) had not received any representations made by providers regarding the role of LEPs in procurement activity. The Skills Funding Agency (SFA) established an External Advisory Group with representation from all provider sectors, the Association of Colleges, Association of Employment and Learning Providers and third sector organisations and also from Local Enterprise Partnerships, including the LEP Network. This provided a forum for the SFA to consult on how European Social Fund (ESF) programme funds would be deployed under the new arrangements. This forum was supported by BIS, SFA and Department for Work and Pensions representation.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-08T15:22:31.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450299/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450299/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","European Social Fund: Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the implications for further education and skills providers of European Social Fund allocations being assigned to local enterprise partnerships, instead of on a co-financing basis; and what representations he has received from further education and skills providers and organisations on the effect of those changes on cashflow and delivery of programmes.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","25736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450300","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>Ed Welsh and Thomas Vogt-Skard are the Cabinet office Non-Executive Directors on the board of IDSL.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-08T11:05:56.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450300/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450300/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Integrated Debt Services: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who represents the Government on the board of Integrated Debt Services Limited.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450301","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>The costs for GOV.UK are accounted for with other costs for the Government Digital Service and published in the Cabinet Office Report and Accounts as part of the Efficiency and Reform Group.</p><p>Departments also produce and publish their own material onto GOV.UK so some costs will rest with them.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-11T12:02:05.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450301/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450301/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Government: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the cost was of guidance published on the gov.uk website in each of the last five years; what the mean and range costs are of producing each piece of advice; and how many pieces of guidance were produced in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","25767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450302","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>As part of my Department's transparency programme, details of Ministerial meetings with external organisations are published on the Cabinet Office website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-transparency-publications</a>.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-08T11:16:42.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450302/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450302/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Cabinet Office: Google","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions have taken place between Ministers in his Department and Google on IT systems used by the Government in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450303","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>Procurement guidance issued by the Crown Commercial Service (CCS) deals with operational matters and clarifies existing policy, set out in the EU Public Procurement Directives and the Public Contracts Regulations (2015), which were subject to Parliamentary process.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-08T16:55:53.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450303/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450303/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2016 to Question 24475, what his policy is on providing for parliamentary scrutiny any revisions to guidance on procurement policy and its relationship to foreign policy.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450304","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-08","<p>Since January 2011, as part of the Government’s transparency programme, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Since 1 April 2015, wider public sector bodies, including local authorities, have also been required to publish details of contracts above the value of £25,000 on Contracts Finder.</p><p>Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: http://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-08T16:56:07.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450304/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450304/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Government Departments: Google","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contracts for delivery of IT services have been concluded between the Government and Google in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","25777"
