"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450308","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government has announced reforms to the business rates retention scheme which mean that, by the end of this Parliament, local government will keep 100% of locally raised business rates and 100% of the growth generated by new development. Over the coming months we will be working with local government on the details of the scheme.</p><p>Ahead of final decisions, it is too early to assess what the impact of the reforms will be on individual areas' spending power.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","25835","2016-02-08T17:40:13.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450308/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450308/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Non-domestic Rates: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Copeland Borough Council's spending power of reforms to business rates announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450309","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-11","<p>Annual funding for the Illegal Money Lending Teams as reported to the Department by National Trading Standards was:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Wales</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16 *</p></td><td><p>£3,097,822</p></td><td><p>£546,674</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>£3,605,286</p></td><td><p>£634,016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>£3,716,789</p></td><td><p>£673,625</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>£3,716,789</p></td><td><p>£595,670</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12**</p></td><td><p>£3,716,789</p></td><td><p>£653,625</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* * Additionally, for 2015/16 the FCA agreed to outsource work to a maximum of £880,000, split £748,000 to the England Team and £132,000 to the Wales Team. The FCA will outsource work to a maximum of £500,000 for 2016/17.</p><p>** Until the creation of NTS in April 2012, the teams were funded directly by BIS.</p><p>BIS has committed to maintaining its funding of the teams at 2015/16 year levels for 2016/17. It is anticipated that levy funding will be in place from 2017/18.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-11T14:39:07.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450309/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450309/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-03","Illegal Money Lending Teams: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 24171, what funding the Illegal Money Lending Team received in each of the last five years; and how much it will receive in each year until it becomes funded through a levy.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450310","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government has announced reforms to the business rates retention scheme which mean that, by the end of this Parliament, local government will keep 100% of locally raised business rates and 100% of the growth generated by new development. Over the coming months we will be working with local government on the details of the scheme.</p><p>Ahead of final decisions, it is too early to assess what the impact of the reforms will be on individual areas' spending power.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","25834","2016-02-08T17:40:13.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450310/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450310/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Non-domestic Rates: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy that business rates generated by new nuclear development in Copeland will be retained by the billing authority.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","25835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450311","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-09","<p>The Government is finalising funding arrangements for the enforcement of illegal money lending. These arrangements will ensure that the enforcement teams have the funding that they need to protect consumers from illegal loan sharks.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-09T15:43:13.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450311/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Illegal Money Lending Teams","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 24171, whether the change in funding for the Illegal Money Lending Team will result in a change in its levels of funding in real terms.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","25727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450312","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>There are several inheritance tax (IHT) reliefs and these have different policy purposes. Transfers between spouses, including civil partners, are exempt from IHT. Taken together with the IHT nil-rate band, these exemptions are designed to allow most estates to be passed on to beneficiaries without an inheritance tax liability. More targeted exemptions and reliefs have different purposes including encouraging charitable giving, ensuring that businesses and farms do not have to be broken up to pay the liability and ensuring estates of those in the armed services and our emergency services who die in active service are exempt from inheritance tax.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T15:53:10.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450312/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450312/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) primary and (b) secondary policy purposes are of inheritance tax relief for estates left on death.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450313","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Location Programme is the result of an extended period of consultation and deliberation. The Department has taken account of a number of criteria in reaching its decisions, including the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply, the cost of buildings and asset value, and the need to retain the staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation. These changes will reduce HMRC’s estates costs by around £100 million a year by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning. The Department plans to update these once discussions have been held with its staff.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s modelling estimates that the majority of staff live within Reasonable Daily Travel of a regional centre. Reasonable Daily Travel is calculated in line with established HR policies and procedures. Every worker at HMRC will have a one-to-one meeting with their manager to discuss their individual circumstances.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","25796","2016-02-11T13:27:38.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450313/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450313/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, at which offices the 4,000 staff of HM Revenue and Customs who are expected to live outside the reasonable travel to work area after the Building Our Future reorganisation work.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450314","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>The Government’s approach to appraisal is set out in the Green Book. This provides a common, standard method for comparing all public spending decisions that use central government funding; the approach to appraising potential PPP projects is consistent with this central guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The quantitative assessment tool was in place from August 2004 until its withdrawal in December 2012, all projects which commenced between these dates should have used the tool. For details of specific projects during this period, please see the spreadsheet ‘Current projects as at 31 March 2014’ at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-projects-2014-summary-data</p><p> </p><p>A replacement quantitative assessment tool has not been issued by HM Treasury due to the limitations of standard models; since December 2012 procuring authorities have undertaken appropriate quantitative assessment in accordance with the principles set out in the Green Book.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-08T16:35:23.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450314/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450314/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department has made on the replacement of the value for money assessment quantitative assessment tool for comparing private finance and conventional procurement options; and which PF1 and PF2 projects used (a) the original value for money assessment quantitative assessment tool or (b) any replacement tool.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","25812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450315","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>Whilst the Treasury does collect and publish information on the unitary charges of PFI projects, we do not collect it broken down into its constituent parts, neither do we have the detailed financial models that would allow us to disaggregate the totals.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-08T16:33:49.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450315/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450315/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which of the unitary charges in the list of private finance initiative projects published by his Department on 15 December 2014 were (a) service charges, (b) interest charges and (c) other costs identified over the course of the contracts.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","25813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450316","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Location Programme is the result of an extended period of consultation and deliberation. The Department has taken account of a number of criteria in reaching its decisions, including the quality of local transport links, the local labour market and future workforce supply, the cost of buildings and asset value, and the need to retain the staff and skills it needs to continue its transformation. These changes will reduce HMRC’s estates costs by around £100 million a year by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC conducted high level People Impact and Equality Assessments to inform its planning. The Department plans to update these once discussions have been held with its staff.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s modelling estimates that the majority of staff live within Reasonable Daily Travel of a regional centre. Reasonable Daily Travel is calculated in line with established HR policies and procedures. Every worker at HMRC will have a one-to-one meeting with their manager to discuss their individual circumstances.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","25820","2016-02-11T13:27:38.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450316/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450316/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish equality impact assessments and cost benefit analysis produced as part of the programme of rationalisation of HM Revenue and Customs offices.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450317","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>Approval to proceed to compulsory redundancy for 152 HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) staff was received from Civil Service Resourcing and the Cabinet Office following consultation with the departmental trade unions and a period of reflection. It was endorsed by HMRC’s Executive Committee and the final decision was taken by the Chief Executive on 28 January 2016.</p><p>The 152 people affected are based in around 50 locations across the UK. HMRC is continuing to seek redeployment solutions for all those who wish it to do so.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","25798","2016-02-11T16:42:47.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450317/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450317/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Revenue and Customs: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when in January 2016 the decision to issue compulsory redundancy notices to 152 HM Revenue and Customs staff was made.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450318","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>Approval to proceed to compulsory redundancy for 152 HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) staff was received from Civil Service Resourcing and the Cabinet Office following consultation with the departmental trade unions and a period of reflection. It was endorsed by HMRC’s Executive Committee and the final decision was taken by the Chief Executive on 28 January 2016.</p><p>The 152 people affected are based in around 50 locations across the UK. HMRC is continuing to seek redeployment solutions for all those who wish it to do so.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","25797","2016-02-11T16:42:47.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450318/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450318/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Revenue and Customs: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, where the 152 staff who have been issued with compulsory redundancy notices by HM Revenue and Customs staff are based.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","25798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450319","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>Making Tax Digital will not involve quarterly tax returns. Instead, this is about making life easier for businesses – saving them time and money. These changes are a central part of a package of reforms that will save businesses £400m in administrative burdens.</p><p> </p><p>Many taxpayers have told HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) that they want more certainty over their tax bill and access to an in-year picture of their tax position. Instead of an onerous tax return, once a quarter businesses will update HMRC from their digital records and in most cases, little or no further entry of information will be needed. These reforms will make it easier for business to understand how much tax they owe, giving them far more certainty over their tax position, helping them budget, invest and grow.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has received a number of representations from individuals, businesses, professional bodies and the software industry about Making Tax Digital. I also refer the honourable Member to my response of 11 January 2016 (with references <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-04/20876/" target="_blank">20876</a> and <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-05/21032/" target="_blank">21032</a>).</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:38:19.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450319/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450319/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Small Businesses: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received over the additional burdens to small businesses of the move to quarterly tax returns.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","25711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450320","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>Information regarding the purchasing power of the sterling compared with other EU Member States is publically available at the following address:</p><p> </p><p>ec.europa.eu/eurostat/tgm/table.do?tab=table&amp;init=1&amp;plugin=1&amp;pcode=tec00120&amp;language=en.</p><p> </p>Details of the proposals for child benefit is subject to the ongoing negotiation.","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T13:32:01.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450320/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450320/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Exchange Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, in which EU countries the purchasing power of sterling is currently less than in the UK; and whether the Government has made an assessment of the likelihood that, under proposals for reform of the UK's relationship with the EU, EU law would require proposed child benefit payment adjustments to be increased in such countries.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","25702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450321","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold this information.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:02:22.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450321/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450321/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Revenue and Customs: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many complaints from members of the public were received by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) relating to the closure of the HMRC enquiry centre in Cardiff in the last 18 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450322","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>The first PF2 projects reached financial close last year. The Treasury will publish the equity return information on PF2 projects periodically.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-08T16:36:32.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450322/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450322/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the equity return information provided as part of all PF2 projects commissioned in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","25744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450323","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>The FCA is an independent, non-governmental organisation, and so it would not be appropriate for the government to intervene in, or comment on, their ongoing investigation into the Connaught Income Fund Series 1.</p><p> </p><p>On 29 January, the FCA published on their website an update to investors on the Connaught Income Fund. This update outlines that a settlement has been reached between the liquidators of the fund and Capita Financial Managers Ltd. The FCA have asked the liquidators to distribute the settlement sum to investors as soon as possible. The update also states that while the FCA’s investigation is ongoing, they will not provide any comments or details on progress because to do so may later turn out to be misleading.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-08T16:43:54.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450323/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450323/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department and the FCA have made on the Connaught Income Fund Series 1.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","25675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450324","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not hold data by constituency and regularly publishes general performance reports at Gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:03:55.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450324/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450324/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many enquiries regarding self-assessment originating from each constituency were handled by HM Revenue and Customs call centres in each of the last three tax years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","25746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450325","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>From 1 April 2016 higher rates of SDLT will be charged on purchases of additional residential properties, such as second homes and buy-to-let properties. The higher rates will be 3 percentage points above the current SDLT rates. This is part of the Government’s commitment to supporting home ownership and first-time buyers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has carefully considered the case where a purchaser buys a new main home in advance of selling an old one. Where there is a temporary overlap between replacing and selling a main residence, the Government intends that higher rates will apply but the purchaser will be entitled to a refund of the higher amounts when they dispose of their previous main residence within 18 months.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has consulted on the changes to ensure they are introduced in a fair way. The final policy design will be confirmed at Budget on 16 March 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:09:48.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450325/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450325/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the planned increase in stamp duty on the ability of people to purchase a retirement property in advance of selling their primary home.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","25814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450326","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>This is a longstanding tax relief which ensures that business payments made to scientific research associations which carry out research relevant to the business can be taken into account in calculating taxable profits.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:06:38.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450326/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450326/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Science: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) primary and (b) secondary policy purposes are of income tax and corporation tax relief on payments to relevant scientific research associations.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450327","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>Relief from stamp duty is available for company reconstructions where the same people hold the same proportion of shares before and after the reconstruction. The relief ensures that stamp duty does not apply where there is no real change in ownership of a company. The relief also recognises that reconstructions of companies often occur for genuine commercial reasons unrelated to tax, so in strictly defined circumstances should be able to take place in a tax neutral way. All claims are adjudicated by HM Revenue and Customs to ensure the strict conditions for relief are met.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:07:30.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450327/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450327/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Stamp Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) primary and (b) secondary policy purposes are of stamp duty exemption for transfers under schemes of company reconstruction and similar arrangements.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450328","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","<p><strong>Supplies of commercial property are subject to a mandatory VAT exemption under the European VAT Directive. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-15T10:13:02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450328/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450328/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) primary and (b) secondary policy purposes are of VAT exemption for supplies of commercial property.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450329","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-08","<p>R&amp;D tax credits support businesses to invest in Research &amp; Development (R&amp;D). They play a key role in the Government’s objective to have a tax system that supports productive investment. A 2015 evaluation by HM Revenue and Customs found that each £1 of tax foregone by R&amp;D tax credits stimulates between £1.53 and £2.35 of additional R&amp;D investment.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-08T16:05:45.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450329/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450329/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-03","Research and Development Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) primary and (b) secondary policy purposes are of research and development tax credits.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","25842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450330","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-10","<p>The Government is working with local partners in the North East to design an implementation plan for the North East devolution deal. Officials based in Cities and Local Growth team will work with local places to monitor the progress of implementation. When the necessary statutory instruments are in place, the Mayor will decide how to monitor the area’s transport policy, and will be directly held to account by local constituents.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-10T16:53:06.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450330/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450330/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Devolution: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2016 to Question 24228, on public transport: North East, what his Department's role is in finalising monitoring arrangements.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","25765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450331","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government has in place a local government led process for the consideration of planning applications for shale gas exploration. As part of this, mineral planning authorities have a responsibility to consider such applicationsunder the Town and Country Planning regime. The Government has taken steps to ensure this locally led regime is effective, as set out in Written Ministerial Statements made on 16 September, HCWS201 and HCWS202. This includes making available £1.2 million to ensure mineral planning authorities have adequate resource to reach timely decisions.</p><p>Community involvement in planning applications and people’s safety and the environment will remain paramount. No decision has been made to take shale gas exploration out of this local government led process and there are no plans currently to consult on such a change.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","25695","2016-02-11T13:22:03.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450331/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450331/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Fracking: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will ensure that decisions on planning applications for fracking are taken within the local government planning process.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","25693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450332","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Government has in place a local government led process for the consideration of planning applications for shale gas exploration. As part of this, mineral planning authorities have a responsibility to consider such applicationsunder the Town and Country Planning regime. The Government has taken steps to ensure this locally led regime is effective, as set out in Written Ministerial Statements made on 16 September, HCWS201 and HCWS202. This includes making available £1.2 million to ensure mineral planning authorities have adequate resource to reach timely decisions.</p><p>Community involvement in planning applications and people’s safety and the environment will remain paramount. No decision has been made to take shale gas exploration out of this local government led process and there are no plans currently to consult on such a change.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","25693","2016-02-11T13:22:03.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450332/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450332/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Fracking: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what consultation he plans to undertake on changes to the planning process for applications for fracking.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","25695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450333","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>Brownfield land is defined as previously developed land in the National Planning Policy Framework. We are consulting on whether it would be beneficial to strengthen national policy on the development of brownfield land for housing. The consultation closes on 22 February.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T13:22:39.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450333/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450333/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to extend the classification criteria of brownfield sites for housebuilding.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","25698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450334","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>It is the responsibility of the housing developer to ensure that work is compliant with the building regulations both during construction and post-construction. During the construction period, the building control body would be responsible for checking compliance. Post-construction, where there is a new home warranty in place, the warranty provider provides cover for up to ten years after construction and can include compliance with aspects of the building regulations.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-11T13:25:13.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450334/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450334/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the post-construction obligations on large volume housing developers in enforcing compliance with building regulations.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","25705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450335","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Department promotes awareness of Help to Buy through the two Government websites Help to Buy and Own Your Home, through regular updates on the Help to Buy Twitter and Facebook accounts and through press advertising to promote Help to Buy: Equity Loan and London Help to Buy.</p><p>Over 62,500 homes have been purchased through Help to Buy: Equity Loan, to end September 2015. On 1 February, we launched London Help to Buy which will enable people to purchase a home with up to 40% equity loan of the purchase price and a deposit as low as 5%. It could potentially help over 10,000 households to purchase a home in London over the next five years.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T17:10:03.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450335/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450335/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to promote Help to Buy.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","25714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450336","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>Shared Ownership has an important role to play in helping those who aspire to home ownership but may be otherwise unable to afford it. The Autumn Statement confirmed £4.1 billion for 135,000 new Help to Buy: Shared Ownership starts by 2021 and we have relaxed restrictions on who can buy Shared Ownership homes. A new prospectus for the Affordable Homes Programme will be published in the spring.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T13:24:25.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450336/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450336/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Shared Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to promote shared ownership.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","25715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450337","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>We are creating a £2 billion long term housing development fund to unlock housing on brownfield land. We will also require local authorities in England to maintain registers of brownfield land that is suitable for housing. In addition we are consulting on whether it would be beneficial to strengthen national planning policy on the development of brownfield land for housing. The consultation closes on 22 February.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-11T17:10:59.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450337/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450337/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to promote the development of brownfield land.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","25716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450338","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-22","<p>This decision has now been announced. The announcement was made on Thursday 18 February.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-22T16:43:48.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450338/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450338/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Route 39 Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to announce a decision on the planning appeal submitted by the Route 39 free school in Torridge.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","25809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450339","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-11","<p>Devolution deals are progressing well across the north having already been agreed with Greater Manchester, Sheffield, Tees Valley, the North East and Liverpool, all of which will see directly elected mayors introduced in return for substantial new powers and budgets. Discussions with other areas across the north are progressing.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-02-11T15:46:52.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450339/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450339/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-03","Devolution: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to devolve powers to the local level under the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","25772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450340","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-11","<p>This information can be found in the 2015 Information Security Breaches Survey [<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/information-security-breaches-survey-2015" target="_blank">Link</a>]. The Government’s National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP) aims to tackle cyber crime and make the UK the safest place in the world to do business in the world. This includes the Cyber Essentials Scheme to protect businesses against common cyber threats and the cyber streetwise campaign which offers simple cyber security advice to small businesses and consumers. In addition to the £860 million investment under the NCSP between 2011-2016, in November 2015 the Chancellor announced a new five year £1.9 billion investment in cyber security to make the UK one of the best protected countries in cyber space.</p><p>All Government departments must adhere to the Government’s Security Policy Framework and are required to report, manage and recover from information risk incidents, including losses of protected personal data and ICT security incidents.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T17:43:56.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450340/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450340/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-03","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) small businesses, (b) large corporations and (c) Government departments and agencies reported breaches of cyber security in 2015.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450341","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-11","<p>At the end of January 2016, 1,674 Cyber essentials and Cyber essentials Plus certificates have been issued, of which 80% were awarded to micro, small and medium-sized businesses.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-11T10:51:43.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450341/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450341/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-03","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) small and medium-sized enterprises and (b) other businesses have signed up to the Cyber Essentials Scheme.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450342","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>The Cyber Streetwise campaign has been supported by fifty-six private sector businesses in a variety of ways. This figure includes membership associations, but excludes public sector organisations such as the police, universities and Neighbourhood Watch.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-11T12:01:08.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450342/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450342/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many UK businesses have participated in the Be Cyber Streetwise campaign.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450343","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>Cyber security skills and talent are vital to protecting the UK. The Cyber Security Challenge UK competition aims to bring more talented people into the cyber security profession and address a critical skills shortage that affects government bodies, businesses and citizens alike. The number of people who have taken part in the Cyber Security Challenge Competition each year since its inception is as follows:</p><p>• 2011 – 4,000;</p><p>• 2012 – 2,785;</p><p>• 2013 – 2,910;</p><p>• 2014 – 2,104;</p><p>• 2015 – 7,018</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-11T12:00:52.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450343/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450343/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450343/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have taken part in the Cyber Security Challenge Competition in each year since its inception.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450344","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>CERT-UK is the UK National Computer Emergency Response Team. CERT-UK advises organisations on what actions to take in the event of a cyber incident and offers advice and guidance on how to mitigate threats pre and post incident through one to one meetings and through its online sharing platform, the Cyber-security Information Sharing Partnership (CiSP). CERT-UK has dealt with 1170 incidents since its launch in March 2014.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","25774","2016-02-11T11:58:35.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450344/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450344/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many organisations have been assisted in recovery from cyber-attack by the Cyber Incident Response Team in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) England and (d) Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450345","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-11","<p>CERT-UK is the UK National Computer Emergency Response Team. CERT-UK advises organisations on what actions to take in the event of a cyber incident and offers advice and guidance on how to mitigate threats pre and post incident through one to one meetings and through its online sharing platform, the Cyber-security Information Sharing Partnership (CiSP). CERT-UK has dealt with 1170 incidents since its launch in March 2014.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","25722","2016-02-11T11:58:35.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450345/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450345/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-03","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many organisations have been assisted in recovery from cyber-attack by the Cyber Incident Response Team in each year since that team was established.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","25774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450346","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-10","<p>Overseas tours for military personnel can be broadly grouped into three categories: operational deployments, exercises and longer-term postings.</p><p>Operational deployment roles are high readiness deployments anywhere in the world where there is an operational requirement and are not family accompanied. UK military personnel are currently performing these roles in parts of Asia, Africa, Europe, the Middle East and the South Atlantic Islands.</p><p>The standard tour length for operational deployments can vary greatly depending on the circumstances but is likely to be six months, with some Service personnel serving up to 12 months or longer.</p><p>Large-scale exercises are conducted in Belize, Canada and Kenya to provide training for UK military operations. There are a small number of permanent UK military staff posted in each location, and these roles are family accompanied. UK military personnel sent to these locations on exercise are not accompanied by their families.</p><p>Permanent or longer-term posted roles or assignments can be family accompanied. Permanent overseas postings which can be family accompanied include Bahrain, Qatar, the USA, Gibraltar, the South Atlantic Islands, the Cyprus Sovereign Base Areas and the United Nations Operation TOSCA, Singapore and European countries. Around 4,600 of these posts are family-accompanied.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","25763 ; 25764","2016-02-10T16:40:09.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450346/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/450346/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-03","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, in which countries British Service personnel are deployed.","true","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","25762"
